    "### Preprocessing\n",
    "Our preprocessing pipeline aims to match and improve upon that of [CITATION?]. The pipeline consists of the following main steps on the playlist names column:\n",
    "#### Homogenization \n",
    "Homogenization is the process of extracting the base form (lemma) of a word. The process consists of two main steps. Firstly we use regular expressions to make all letters lowercase and strip out punctuation. Next we break all the words in the names into tokens and lemmatize them (e.g., converting \"workouts\" to \"workout\"). Practically this is done using the Natural Language Toolkit (NLTK) library. The aim with this process is to transform the messy inconsistent user-generated names into a standard format, which makes string matching more accurate in the clustering algorithms."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Column 'homogenized_playlist' already exists. Skipping homogenization.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from preprocessing.preprocessor import homogenize_playlists\n",
    "df = homogenize_playlists(df)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Entity Filtering\n",
    "The goal of entity filtering is to remove playlists that lack contextual information, or are strictly based on named entities (like specific artists, or bands). As we are trying to cluster based on the context described in the name, we filter out these non-contextual playlists to ensure our clustering models learn situational patterns rather than grouping artist discographies together.\n",
    "\n",
    "To do this we run a strict filtering process, where we compare the playlist names against the artists present in the dataset, along with a set of predefined genres. To take it one step further, we use the spaCy NLP library to analyze the grammatical structure for further named entity recognition. The model looks for entities tagged as \"person\", \"org\" or \"work of art\", and removes playlists where this consists of 80% or more of the name. We also implement a \"rescue mechanism\", in which the script checks tokens for adjectives or verbs and ensures these playlists are kept, as the presence of an action or description implies context, regardless of the rest of the name."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "\n",
      "[INFO] 'spotify_fully_processed.parquet' already exists. Loading it directly...\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from preprocessing.preprocessor import filter_entities\n",
    "df = filter_entities(df)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Stop-word Filtering\n",
    "Stop-word filtering removes the words, which we do not want to expand and cluster on. Stop words define any words that are often used without providing semantic meaning. In our case we filter on both classic stop words such as \"as\" and \"a\" along with music specific stop words such as \"track\" and \"playlist\", which do not provide meaning to the playlist name. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "\n",
      "Stop words already filtered. Skipping.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from preprocessing.preprocessor import remove_stop_words\n",
    "df = remove_stop_words(df)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "#### Feature Expansion\n",
    "The `expand_feature` function is responsible for the text preprocessing, which enriches the short strings, e.g. a playlist name, but appending related words to it. This technique provides more context for text-mining algorithms like TF-IDF. The flow of the function is the following:\n",
    "1. First the input gets validated, an empty string is returned if not. \n",
    "2. A set is maintaned which stores the words, preventing duplicate entries. \n",
    "3. We then split the input strings into individual words and process them one by one. For each word, WordNet is used to find\n",
    "    - Synonyms (Lemmas), which contain the exact same meaning. \n",
    "    - Hypernyms expanding general category words ('guitar' -> 'stringed instrument'). \n",
    "4. Lastly, the underscores from WordNet terms are replaced with spaces, and the final deduplicated set of original words, synonyms, and hypernyms is returned as a single, space-separated string. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "\n",
      "Expanded features already exist. Skipping expansion step.\n"
     ]
